      <h2>Critical thinking</h2>
      <ul>
        <li><strong><a href="https://www.criticalthinking.org" target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer">Foundation for Critical Thinking</a></strong> — Research-based frameworks, lesson plans, and assessment tools for teaching critical thinking at all levels.</li>
        <li><strong><a href="https://yourlogicalfallacyis.com" target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer">Your Logical Fallacy Is</a></strong> — Visual guide to common logical fallacies. Printable poster available.</li>
        <li><strong><a href="https://yourbias.is" target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer">Your Bias Is</a></strong> — Companion to the fallacy guide, covering cognitive biases.</li>
        <li><strong><a href="https://www.coursera.org/learn/critical-thinking-skills" target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer">Coursera: Critical Thinking Skills</a></strong> — Free online course from the University of London.</li>
      </ul>

      <h2>Science education</h2>
      <ul>
        <li><strong><a href="https://ncse.ngo" target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer">National Center for Science Education</a></strong> — Defends the teaching of evolution and climate science in public schools. Resources for teachers and parents.</li>
        <li><strong><a href="https://www.khanacademy.org" target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer">Khan Academy</a></strong> — Free courses in biology, chemistry, physics, and cosmology.</li>
        <li><strong><a href="https://undsci.berkeley.edu" target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer">Understanding Science (UC Berkeley)</a></strong> — How science works — a free resource for teachers and students.</li>
      </ul>

      <h2>Philosophy for young people</h2>
      <ul>
        <li><strong><a href="https://www.teachingchildrenphilosophy.org" target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer">Teaching Children Philosophy</a></strong> — Discussion guides linked to children's books. Free and well-organized.</li>
        <li><strong><a href="https://plato.stanford.edu" target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer">Stanford Encyclopedia of Philosophy</a></strong> — The definitive free reference for academic philosophy.</li>
        <li><strong><a href="https://www.philosophyexperiments.com" target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer">Philosophy Experiments</a></strong> — Interactive thought experiments for exploring ethical and philosophical questions.</li>
      </ul>

      <h2>Debate and rhetoric</h2>
      <ul>
        <li><strong><a href="https://www.ironchariots.wiki" target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer">Iron Chariots Wiki</a></strong> — Counter-apologetics resource covering common religious arguments and responses.</li>
        <li><strong><a href="https://rationalwiki.org" target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer">RationalWiki</a></strong> — Community wiki analyzing pseudoscience, authoritarianism, and fundamentalism.</li>
      </ul>

      <h2>For educators</h2>
      <ul>
        <li><strong><a href="https://www.campquest.org/educators" target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer">Camp Quest Educator Resources</a></strong> — Secular education activities and curricula.</li>
        <li><strong><a href="https://www.secularstudents.org/resources" target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer">Secular Student Alliance Resources</a></strong> — Starting and running secular student groups.</li>
      </ul>

